The Financial Secretary, with the assistance of the Secretary for Financial Services and the Treasury, is responsible for maintaining the stability and soundness of the financial system in Hong Kong, as well as policies to preserve Hong Kong’s status as an international financial centre. To implement these policies, the duties of the Commissioner for Financial Management include:
- promoting the overall stability and effective functioning of the banking system;
- cooperating with other relevant institutions and organizations to develop the debt market;
- handling matters relating to the issuance and circulation of legal tender notes and coins;
- promoting the safety and efficiency of financial infrastructure through the development of payment, clearing and settlement systems, and operating such systems where appropriate; and
- cooperating with other relevant institutions and organizations to foster confidence in Hong Kong’s currency and financial system, and implementing appropriate development measures to help strengthen the international competitiveness of Hong Kong’s financial services.

Monetary base (Table 1) includes:
- Liability certificates (providing full backing for banknotes issued by the three issuing banks);
- Government-issued circulating banknotes and coins;
- The aggregate balance of settlement accounts held at the Monetary Authority (i.e., total balance); and
- Foreign exchange fund bills and bonds issued by the Monetary Authority on behalf of the government.

The Hong Kong Monetary Authority’s Fintech Facilitation Office continues to collaborate with banking departments to implement the "Fintech 2025" strategy, promoting widespread adoption of fintech and enhancing Hong Kong's position as a fintech hub in Asia. Key initiatives this year include:
- Promoting the application of regulatory technology and conducting fintech application assessments;
- Advancing work on central bank digital currency (CBDC) at the wholesale level to improve cross-border payments;
- Deepening research on the issuance of retail-level CBDC (i.e., "Digital Hong Kong Dollar" or e-HKD);
- Launching the "Commercial Data Exchange";
- Strengthening talent development;
- Leveraging policy support to foster the fintech ecosystem;
- Enhancing cross-border fintech cooperation; and
- Promoting broader adoption of the Fast Payment System “TransferFast” (FPS).

The Foreign Exchange Fund Advisory Committee has established the following investment objectives for the Fund:  
(i) to protect capital;  
(ii) to ensure that the overall monetary base is at all times fully supported by highly liquid U.S. dollar assets;  
(iii) to ensure that sufficient liquidity is maintained to support monetary and financial stability; and  
(iv) subject to compliance with the above (i) to (iii), to maximize investment returns in order to safeguard the Fund's long-term purchasing power.

The Risk Committee’s scope of authority is as follows:
- To identify potential risks and threats faced by the Authority and develop strategies to mitigate their impact;
- To review existing risk management systems across departments, identify potential vulnerabilities and significant risks, and ensure appropriate measures are in place to address them;
- To standardize risk assessment criteria and methodologies, and to prioritize resource allocation based on identified risks; and
- To promote and strengthen a risk management culture within the Authority, fostering appropriate delegation of authority and monitoring.

The audit procedures for the valuation of financial assets and financial liabilities measured at fair value include:  
- Understanding the valuation procedures for different categories of financial assets and liabilities, including related monitoring controls;  
- Evaluating and testing monitoring controls, including application controls related to computer systems;  
- Obtaining confirmations regarding the valuation, existence, rights and obligations, and completeness of financial assets and liabilities;  
- Verifying prices against independent sources when market quotations are used;  
- Evaluating the appropriateness of the valuation method and the reasonableness of related assumptions, and verifying parameters against independent sources when the parameters used in the valuation method are based on observable market data; and  
- Evaluating the appropriateness of the valuation method, as well as the reasonableness of related assumptions and parameters, when the parameters used in the valuation method are not based on observable market data.

During the audit process conducted in accordance with the Audit Office's auditing standards, I will apply professional judgment and maintain a professional skeptical attitude. I will also:
- Identify and assess the risk of material misstatements in the financial statements due to fraud or error; design and perform audit procedures to address these risks; and obtain sufficient and appropriate audit evidence to support my opinion. Since fraud may involve collusion, falsification, intentional omission, false statements, or overriding of internal controls, the risk of not detecting material misstatements due to fraud is higher than the risk of not detecting those due to error;
- Understand the internal controls relevant to the audit in order to design appropriate audit procedures. However, this is not intended to express an opinion on the effectiveness of the group's internal controls;
- Evaluate whether the accounting policies adopted by the Financial Management Officer are appropriate, and whether the accounting estimates and related disclosures made are reasonable;
- Determine whether the Financial Management Officer's use of the going concern basis for accounting is appropriate, and based on the audit evidence obtained, determine whether there are significant uncertainties related to events or circumstances that may cast significant doubt on the group's ability to continue as a going concern. If I believe that significant uncertainties exist, it is necessary to draw the users' attention to the relevant disclosures in the financial statements in the auditor's report. If the relevant disclosures are insufficient, I will issue an auditor's report with a non-unmodified opinion. My conclusion is based on the audit evidence obtained up to the date of the auditor's report. However, future events or circumstances may lead to the group's inability to continue as a going concern;
- Evaluate the overall presentation, structure, and content of the financial statements, including disclosures, and whether the financial statements fairly present transactions and events; and
- Obtain sufficient and appropriate audit evidence regarding the financial information of entities or business activities within the group in order to express an opinion on the financial statements. I am responsible for directing, supervising, and performing the group audit. I bear full responsibility for my audit opinion.
